{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17473416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17473416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:08:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2409"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2409"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.05,0.01,0.61,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53073"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2409"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2409"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38484"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"295"},{"type":"tags","id":"527"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"5771"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1734"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1887"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17013"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40965"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42485"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43143"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44074"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53073","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/53073"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 14-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department of a rural hospital with her parent, complaining of a two-day history of progressive lower abdominal pain, accompanied by fever, nausea and anorexia. The pain was initially felt as a dull ache in the central abdomen, before migrating into the right lower abdomen. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She is sexually active with a partner of two months and reports always using barrier protection. Her last menstrual period was three weeks ago, with smaller volume blood loss than usual. On examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 105/min, blood pressure 110/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Her abdomen is soft, with some tenderness to palpation in the right lower quadrant. There is mild percussion tenderness over this region. Bowel sounds are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum beta-HCG","Transvaginal ultrasound","C-reactive protein","Urine beta-HCG","Complete blood examination"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn a sexually active female presenting with abdominal pain, pregnancy-related conditions, including ectopic pregnancy, must be considered first and foremost. Despite the patient\u0027s report of consistent barrier protection use, contraceptive failure is still possible. The \u003Cstrong\u003Eurine beta-HCG\u003C/strong\u003E test is the most important initial investigation in this scenario to rule out pregnancy, particularly ectopic pregnancy, which can have severe consequences if missed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBarrier methods like condoms have higher failure rates compared to other contraceptive methods. The typical failure rate for male condoms is estimated to be 15-18% (2% with perfect use), significantly higher than long-acting reversible contraception methods (\u0026lt;1%). Additionally, the patient\u0027s report of a lighter than usual menstrual period three weeks ago could potentially represent early pregnancy bleeding rather than a true period.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eserum beta-HCG\u003C/strong\u003E test is also a valid option for detecting pregnancy, but it takes longer to obtain results and is more invasive than a urine test. In an emergency setting, a urine beta-HCG is preferred as the initial test due to its rapid results and non-invasive nature.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Etransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can be helpful in diagnosing ectopic pregnancy, but it would only be performed after a positive pregnancy test. Moreover, in a 14-year-old patient, a transabdominal approach would be preferred initially.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EC-reactive protein\u003C/strong\u003E is an inflammatory marker that can be elevated in various conditions, including appendicitis. While it might be useful in the diagnostic workup, it is not the most critical initial test in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecomplete blood examination\u003C/strong\u003E might reveal an elevated white cell count, which can be seen in various surgical causes of abdominal pain such as appendicitis. However, it has low specificity and does not help rule out ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, while all these investigations may have a role in the patient\u0027s workup, the urine beta-HCG is the most critical initial test to perform, as it guides further management and helps avoid potentially missing a life-threatening ectopic pregnancy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute lower abdominal pain in a woman of child-bearing age should be assumed to be pregnancy related until proven otherwise.","Urine beta-HCG is the most important initial investigation for abdominal pain in sexually active females to rule out ectopic pregnancy.","Barrier contraception methods have higher failure rates compared to long-acting reversible contraception methods."],"references":["Stoddard A, McNicholas C, Peipert JF. Efficacy and Safety of Long-Acting Reversible Contraception. Drugs (New York, NY). 2011 May;71(8):969\u201380."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38484"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2409"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"38484","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/38484"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-16T11:25:33+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-22T08:11:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2409"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"53073"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"23","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/23"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd30","name":"Obstetrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"